Collection: Barcelona Expert Center SMOS Soil Moisture
Product: Barcelona Expert Center SMOS Soil Moisture L4 1km v06.0
Description: Surface soil moisture estimates generated by downscaling of the SMOS L3 soil moisture v4.0 (at 25 km resolution) though a linear regression model of SSM with land surface temperature (LST) and normalized difference vegetation index (NDVI)

Collection: SMAP-Derived 1-km Downscaled Surface Soil Moisture Product
Product: SMAP-Derived 1-km Downscaled Surface Soil Moisture Product, Version 1
Description: Surface Soil Moisture estimates from the L-band radiometer Soil Moisture Active Passive (SMAP) mission downscaled using a physical model that relates the same-day overpass SMAP SSM difference to the surface temperature.

Collection: Global Gravity-based Groundwater Product (G3P) Groundwater Storage Anomalies
Product: Global Gravity-based Groundwater Product (G3P) Groundwater Storage Anomalies v1.11
Description: The Global Gravity-based Groundwater Product (G3P) provides groundwater storage anomalies (GWSA) extracted from the GRACE(-FO) terrestrial water storage (TWS) through a subtraction of independently evaluated water cycle storage comparments.

Collection: Global Gravity-based Groundwater Product (G3P) Terrestrial Water Storage
Product: Global Gravity-based Groundwater Product (G3P) Terrestrial Water Storage v1.11
Description: The Global Gravity-based Groundwater Product (G3P) provides terrestrial water storage (TWS) derved from the GRACE(-FO) mission gravity field measurements .

The product is characterized by the integration of GPM Late run precipitation estimates and SM2RAIN-derived rainfall. The soil moisture-based estimates are obtained through the application of SM2RAIN to ASCAT retrievals. The two products are merged with a triple collocation technique (third product: ERA5 Land precipitation). Prior the merging the data are downscaled at 1 km spatial resolution using CHELSA (1 km) climatology. The merging technique allows to obtain a high-resolution product (1km-24 hour) over Europe. The product has been developed in the framework of the 4DHydro project for the entire ASCAT era (2007-2022).

Prior the merging the data are downscaled at 1 km spatial resolution using CHELSA (1 km) climatology. The merging technique allows to obtain a high-resolution product (1km-24 hour) over Europe. The product has been developed in the framework of the 4DHydro project for the entire ASCAT era (2007-2022).

The two products are merged with a triple collocation technique (third product: ERA5 Land precipitation). Prior the merging the data are downscaled at 1 km spatial resolution using CHELSA (1 km) climatology. The merging technique allows to obtain a high-resolution product (1km-24 hour) over Europe. The product has been developed in the framework of the 4DHydro project for the entire ASCAT era (2007-2022).

The product is characterized by the integration of GPM Late run precipitation estimates and SM2RAIN-derived rainfall. The soil moisture-based estimates are obtained through the application of SM2RAIN to ASCAT retrievals. The two products are merged with a triple collocation technique (third product: ERA5 Land precipitation). Prior the merging the data are downscaled at 1 km spatial resolution using CHELSA (1 km) climatology. The merging technique allows to obtain a high-resolution product (1km-24 hour) over Tugela basin. The product has been developed in the framework of the 4DHydro project for the entire ASCAT era (2007-2022).

Prior the merging the data are downscaled at 1 km spatial resolution using CHELSA (1 km) climatology. The merging technique allows to obtain a high-resolution product (1km-24 hour) over Tugela basin. The product has been developed in the framework of the 4DHydro project for the entire ASCAT era (2007-2022).

The two products are merged with a triple collocation technique (third product: ERA5 Land precipitation). Prior the merging the data are downscaled at 1 km spatial resolution using CHELSA (1 km) climatology. The merging technique allows to obtain a high-resolution product (1km-24 hour) over Tugela basin. The product has been developed in the framework of the 4DHydro project for the entire ASCAT era (2007-2022).

The high resolution satellite precipitation product is based on the integration of multiple precipitation and rainfall datasets to generate a high spatial (1 km) and temporal (daily) resolution precipitation product over the Mediterranean area. The following precipitation and rainfall datasets are downscaled and merged together: GPM-Late run; CPC; H SAF h120. All these products are originally at coarse spatial resolution (>10 km) and have been downscaled to 1 km spatial resolution using CHELSA (1 km) climatology. The three products are then merged with a triple collocation technique. In the areas covered by snow only GPM-Late run and CPC are merged together using the triple collocation to obtain the relative weights (third product: ERA5 Land precipitation). The product has been developed in the framework of the 4D-MED Hydrology project. The product is available in the period 2015-2022.

A rainfall product based only on the application of SM2RAIN algorithm to ASCAT soil moisture observations is under development in the framework of H SAF project. The rainfall dataset covers the period 2007-2022 taking advantages of the long record of ASCAT retrieval. The product is available on a global scale at daily temporal resolution over a regular grid of 10 km. The product has been release up to December 2022.

EMO (European Meteorological Observations) is a European high-spatial and temporal resolution (daily) data set . EMO is provided within the Copernicus Emergency Management Service and includes several variables. Among the released variables the product provides total precipitation. The insitu observations are quality checked and then interpolated through SPHEREMAP and Yamamoto methods. Further information on the methods used can be found in the below scientific publication of the dataset. EMO is currently available in two spatial resolutions: EMO-5 provides grids with a spatial resolution of 5kmx5km and covers the time period from 1990 to 2019. EMO-1 provides grids with a spatial resolution of 1arcminx1arcmin (approx. 1.5km) and covers the time period from 1990-2022. EMO-1 was adopted in this project.

EMO is provided within the Copernicus Emergency Management Service and includes several variables. Among the released variables the product provides total precipitation. The insitu observations are quality checked and then interpolated through SPHEREMAP and Yamamoto methods. Further information on the methods used can be found in the below scientific publication of the dataset. EMO is currently available in two spatial resolutions: EMO-5 provides grids with a spatial resolution of 5kmx5km and covers the time period from 1990 to 2019. EMO-1 provides grids with a spatial resolution of 1arcminx1arcmin (approx. 1.5km) and covers the time period from 1990-2022. EMO-1 was adopted in this project.

Collection: precipitation Estimation from Remotely Sensed Information using Artificial Neural Networks  Cloud Classification System
Product: precipitation Estimation from Remotely Sensed Information using Artificial Neural Networks  Cloud Classification System
Description: PERSIANN-CCS (precipitation Estimation from Remotely Sensed Information using Artificial Neural Networks  Cloud Classification System) is developed by the Center for Hydrometeorology and Remote Sensing (CHRS) at the University of California Irvine (UCI). The product is based on the use of neural network function  procedures to compute rainfall rate at each 0.25 x 0.25 pixel through infrared images provided by geostationary satellites. Rainfall product covers 60S to 60N globally.

The Global Satellite Mapping of precipitation (GSMAP) is developed by JAXA. The product takes advantages of the Global precipitation Measurement (GPM) mission constellation satellites to provide hourly rain rates. The rainfall estimation is based on the merging of microwave and infrared retrievals through LEO and GEO platforms. The product covers 60S to 60N globally.

The Climate Hazards Group InfraRed precipitation (CHIRP) is a quasi-global rainfall data set. The product uses infrared data to retrieve precipitation at high resolution. The data set runs from 1981 to the near 2024.The CHIRP satellite was developed by the US Geological Survey (USGS) in collaboration with the Climate Hazards Group at the University of California. CHIRP uses TIR satellite rainfall estimates combined with the globally gridded satellite from National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) to produce the rainfall dataset.The CHIRP product provides satellite estimate at high spatiotemporal resolution covering regions between 50 S to 50 N of latitudes. The CHIRP rainfall datasets are available for the period 1981 to near-2024.

Collection: ENSEMBLES daily gridded observational dataset for precipitation
Product: ENSEMBLES daily gridded observational dataset for precipitation
Description: E-OBS is a daily gridded land-only observational dataset over Europe. The blended time series from the station network of the European Climate Assessment & Dataset (ECA&D) project form the basis for the E-OBS gridded dataset. All station data are sourced directly from the European National Meteorological and Hydrological Services (NMHSs) or other data holding institutions. For a considerable number of countries the number of stations used is the complete national network and therefore much more dense than the station network that is routinely shared among NMHSs (which is the basis of other gridded datasets). The density of stations gradually increases through collaborations with NMHSs within European research contracts.

Collection: Spanish Automatic System of Hydrologic Information
Product: Spanish Automatic System of Hydrologic Information
Description: The Spanish Automatic System of Hydrologic Information (SAHI) includes precipitation data gathered from 333 stations over the Ebro basin every 15 minutes. All the data has been gathered for the 2015-2021 time period. The data have been resampled over 1km grid.
